,Recommended,312230,25678951,"Posted: 24 September, 2016",all,r0b0_j0,"If you, like me, love mid- to late-90's FPS games like System Shock or Deus Ex, you're likely to enjoy this game. It's kind of amazing how much it feels like a game of that era just on a modern engine. Complete lack of guidance means lots of exploration and non-linear gameplay.There is one very strange design choice by the devs which is to erase all your save data after you beat the game. So there is no going back to further explore the ship and find things you missed once you trigger an ending. You must restart. I found this disappointing since I had no warning it would happen, so I couldn't go back and explore the ship more in the state it was in right before finishing the game. Actually, this was so bizarre to me that I thought it was a bug; however, a dev responded to me to let me know this was a completely intentional design choice.I still recommend the game, but I think you should just go in knowing you'll have to replay the whole thing to make different choices later in the game. I was happy with my choices (which is why I chose them first!), but I wanted to play through the others without needing to tediously repeat the rest of the game. So even though I thoroughly enjoyed my playthrough, I was left with a bad feeling of disappointment once it ended and the title screen returned missing the option to Continue from a save. Knowing this in advance, I think you can go in and enjoy it without any feelings of disappointment.Overall the experience is very unique and interesting, and the narrative well-told. And it was fun."
,Recommended,312230,20467106,"Posted: 11 January, 2016",all,The Jizz Kid,"This might just be one of my favorite games.Now don't be fooled, this isn't a shooter, at least not really. It has shooting in it, yes, but that's not the focus and there are a limited number of enemies which will never respawn. The map is also fairly small but very easy to navigate once you've been through once or twice (and get the lights on) I'd say this is far more of a puzzle game with an incredible atmosphere. The majority of the gameplay revolves around puzzle solving while occasionally shooting robots. The puzles for the most part aren't all that difficult, with the exception of one which leads you to one of the three endings. The minimalist style might be a bit offputting depending on your sensibilites but I personaly thought it looked pretty nice. (again, after I got the lights on, Before then it COULD be a bit difficult to figure out what you're doing or where you're going)Now, onto the thing the game get's REALLY right: atmosphere. This game scares the absolute♥♥♥♥♥♥out of me, but not because of cheap and ♥♥♥♥♥♥ jumpscares. From the very second you step out of your little pod you are instilled with a deep sense of dread and a feeling of ""something ain't right here..."" There are a handful of scares but you could go through the game and completely miss all of them because there isn't some ♥♥♥♥♥♥ musical sting to startle you and in most cases when they happened I spent a second asking myself ""Did I actually see that?"" and that is what I love so much about this game, it's smart with its scares and baths the entire experience in a rich atmosphere that stuck with me even after I turned the game off.The voice acting in this game is incredible as well, at least for the most part. I personally thought the voice actor they had for Solomon Agnew stole the show and the other two voice actors they had weren't quite on par with his performance. Not to imply they were bad, quite the contrary, they just weren't quite as good and it was pretty noticeable to me.The game however is pretty short (maybe 1.5-2 hours if you're quick about things, 3 if you take your time a bit) and despite being very replayable I don't know if that's really worth the $10 it's being sold for. Additionally the game doesn't seem to be optimized very well. I'm not playing on a very poweful machine but I can generally get away with playing most modern indies on mid to lower settings, but Spirits of Xanadu had very frequent framerate drops and even on the absolute lowest settings I was barely pushing 20 fps most of the time so if you're running on a budget machine keep that in mind. The default controls are pretty wacky as well so before you start the game I'd highly recommend going through and changing everything to your liking, as well as lowering the mouse sensitivity. Speaking of the mouselook, perhaps it's just me but the mouselook didn't feel very great in this game. I can't quite nail down what it is but now matter how much I fiddled with the sensitivity and whatnot it just never felt quite right.All that said though, if you're looking for an atmospheric horror game with a super solid story then Spirits of Xanadu is gonna be exactly what you're looking for. Seriously, please please please play this game and give these guys your money, they really deserve it.UPDATE: So sometime before I wrote this review an update was rolled out that was at least partially focused on optimization and the game runs like a dream on my computer now. There are also a few things I wanted to mention but left out of my inital review because at the time of writing I hadn't actually played the game in some time and was just going off about a dozen or so YouTube videos. 1. You can choose between a female and male character. It literally doesn't do anything other than change the grunts you make when you're injured but it's a neat little addition nonetheless.2. There are 4 different difficulties, one of which being a peaceful mode that makes it so the enemies won't attack you unless you shoot first. I particularly like that one for repeat playthroughs because for me the second (and subsequent) run through the game was a ""Lets find the things I missed the first time!"" kind of run and it's nice to not have to worry about the bots going after you.3. The endings. I mentioned that there was more than one ending but I didn't go any deeper than that and I thought I should. There's your standard good and bad ending (Although they won't be exactly what you think, at least not right off the bat) and there is also a really neat ambiguous and kinda trippy ending that I really like but is a massive pain to actually achieve (there are walkthroughs for those of us who simply don't have the time/brain power to figure it all out) Those endings are part of what provide the game wiht so much replayability.4. The characters. What kind of reviewer am I to mention voice actors without mentioning characters? Well it's simple, I'm not a professional. Anyway, There are three main characters in the game; Solomon Agnew, Lucy Zhao, and Cornell Johns. You never meet any of them throughout the game but in listening to the various audiologs in the game you really get a sense as to who each of these people were. I felt like I really knew these chracters as people which makes it all the more hearbreaking as you piece everything together and learn of their fates and that really is a testament to the strength of the writing and voice acting.Another thing I absolutely need to mention is that the mouselook is fine. The issues I was experiencing I think were directly related to the low framerates I was getting and had absolutely nothing to do with the game itself. After the optimization update it feels great."
,Recommended,312230,17463671,"Posted: 9 August, 2015",all,Teuton,"Spirits of Xanadu will scratch your moody sci-fi horror itch. We all have that itch, because for some reason not many devs tackle this genre. I enjoyed my playthrough and there's even three different endings that require some work and a lot of exploring and decision-making on your own.What I liked is that you truly have some freedom of choice here. You board the Xanadu, you find out what's going on, and then you decide how to apply that knowledge. You'll get rewarded with one of the respective outcomes. You have to do all the exploring and thinking yourself, so it has that nice early 90s feel to it.However, for the price I expected more depth and complexity. The combat is rather bland and generic, I think I saw some of these guns and models in other Unity games before. This is somewhat of a mood-killer. (EDIT: saw it in ""King of the Wood"" which was made by the same devs. So disregard that.)I hope the devs keep working together. I'd be excited to see another game with this flavor."
76561198006541362,Recommended,312230,16671673,"Posted: 24 June, 2015",all,stranger1982,"Something happened on the starship Xanadu and it's up to you to find out why all its crew seem to have disappeared into thin air after what seems to be a bout of sudden madness.Spirits of Xanadu is clearly inspired by System Shock and offers similar gameplay albeit in a very limited setting and with not many technical improvements over its predecessor.PROS:-the art style is very reminiscent of System Shock-good ambient sound design, the Xanadu systems come to life suddendly, sometimes producing ominous noises that keep you on edge: voice acting on audio logs is also pretty good-an excellent psychological thriller with horror/sci-fi elements: Xanadu's story is really well done and slowly unfolds through audio logs and pages-three different endings depending on which clues you uncover and decide to follow-a few interesting puzzles-quite a few secrets for those patient and/or lucky enough to find them: said secrets can unlock new endings, give you access to secret areas and/or reward you with an achievement-the game manages to create a good sense of tension and estrangement-several difficulty levels including a peaceful mode where those so inclined can enjoy the story without combatCONS:-graphics are quite bland, especially robot models, and the weapon effecs are pretty bad-weak weapon sounds-the combat feels a bit clunky overall due to aiming being a bit sluggish-the robots are generally uninspired, turrets and droids are basically copypasted from System Shock 2 while flying robots are a bit of a pain to fight due to their erratic movements-if you do not like exploring looking for clues and just try to fix the ship right away you could be done with the game in less than half an hour, even exploring the game isn't that long due to the pretty small map-some clues can be very cryptic or hidden extremely wellhttp://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=468031099Spirits of Xanadu really excels in its atmosphere and story and is a really good proposition for those fondly remembering System Shock.Sadly the game suffers from a low budget overall, its graphics are really plain and the small map can't provide a lengthy experience to the player: the initially menacing robots also eventually become pretty trivial once you get a better weapon and this mars the sense of uneasiness that the game worked so hard to create.Overall Xanadu is a well crafted journey and can be a good purchase for those with a System Shock itch to scratch as long as you're ok with its limited scope and somewhat low production values: said limits make it hard to recommend at full price though so wait for a sale."
