76561198083051773,Recommended,312230,20709425,"Posted: 23 January, 2016",all,Felli,"Spirits of Xanadu is pretty much proof that a game doesn't need to look 'next-gen' to be worth playing. It's a neat little first-person adventure/shooter, with a psychological premise, more than a blood and guts free-for-all.This little gem popped up in my discovery queue after I had been playing Cradle for a while. It was on sale so I thought, why not? It seemed to have a similar type of theme and story so I gave it a go. I'm not good with things like jumpscare or torture so I was relieved to find this game did psychological horror perfectly without the need for such gimmicks. From beginning to end you feel incredibly uneasy, jumpy even. Every corner, every hallway makes you look behind you and every so often, you'll find yourself asking if what just flickered in your sight, too brief to catch, was ineed real.One of the most intriguing concepts of the entire game are the little 'events' that trigger from time to time. Without giving anything away, it catches your attention every time and keeps you alert and if nothing else, nervous.The story is extremely well written in it's simplicity and gives you just enough about each character to visualize their personalities while still letting your own mind shape the bigger picture. There isn't a lot of story 'visible', it's all hidden in the bits and pieces of the logs left behind by each of the crew. The story unfolds itself only if you seek it out actively, rather than force it upon you. This to me is much more rewarding.The controls are rather straightforward, if a bit awkward at first with a controller. However once you get started it's smooth and responsive.It's a short game, 4-6 hours if you take your time, but it's a GOOD 4-6 hours and worth an extra playthrough if you're looking for the multiple endings. Not all games have to be long to be memorable.This look of the game really does fall in with the 80's sci-fi vibe they were going for and the simplistic visuals actually drew me in more than pushed me away. No graphic glitches to be seen and let's just say trying to line up that basketball shot is nearly as difficult in game as it is in real life. The space, despite it's simplicity feels in scale and there's a ton of small things to investigate. From the old boomboxes that play actual music, to a toaster you can interact and even donuts and soda you can snack on in passing, it's clear the Devs were looking at the little things that bring you into a scene.One of the most memorable things to me was seeing the signage on the ship written in both chinese characters and in English, and how that detail emphasizes more about the crew aboard the ship. A lot of care went into crafting the small universe.It's worth picking up for sure if you have the chance and like a sci-fi story that doesn't hand you all the details on a plate."
