76561198083068272,Recommended,312230,18961497,"Posted: 8 November, 2015",all,TheBeak,"Spirits of Xanadu is a fun, flawed take on the first person adventure/horror genre with sci-fi twists that reckon of System Shock 2, Alien Isolation, Event Horizon and other deep space, science fiction creepfests.  My time with the game was well-spent even if it was a bit short overall.  In the game you play as the stalwart, lone space technician who docks with the Xanadu in order to fix its systems, find out what happened to the crew and bring that sucker back to Earth.Those looking for high-tech, top-tier graphics won't get 'em here, but the old school flavor and visual design does lend Xanadu some atmosphere and weirdness that is unique.  They won't push your PC to the max, yet they look good and are perfectly dim n' grungy with dynamic lightning and some vibrant color hues shaking things up.  Where Xanadu shines even brighter is in the sound department.  You'll frequently find yourself looking over your shoulder to find out the source of various robotic chirps, whirrs and buzzes.  My dog would bark at the computer as I performed various actions which is a pretty good sign.  She normally could give a ruff less if I'm playing a game.The meat of Xanadu lies within its gameplay.  You're free to explore the ship at your pace, opening drawers, activing utilities, fixing broken ship systems, reading files, collecting audio logs, etc.  There is no voice acting from your character so it's up to the audio logs to provide you with important details and they get the job done admirably with solid writing and above-par narration from the cast.  You can literally beat this game quickly or take your time with it (which is what I chose to do) and there's not much in terms of waypoints, guidance or hand-holding.  The way you feel like you are the trigger and catalyst for everything that happens in the game is immersive and welcome in this day and age.  You have a vague sense of what to do but the HOW is on your shoulders.Roughly 75% of the gameplay revolves around finding as much info as you can find and getting the ship in flying shape while the remaining 25% revolves around combat.  There are only a few guns to find and if you don't take the time to thoroughly explore you're probably going to miss at least one on your first playthrough.  You'll face opposition in the form of different robots controlled by the ship's defense AI and even on the hard difficulty setting they put up a decent fight.  Your character isn't Herculean and a few successive beatings will kill you, so you need to take careful aim and adopt the ol' shoot first/ask questions later strategy.  The shooting is completely serviceable but not top-tier FPS; charmingly adding to the tension of trying to survive.  Even if you die you don't lose any progress and save stations are scattered generously enough around the Xanadu that you will never lose giant chunks of playtime.  Some of these things make Xanadu a tad on the easy side, even if you bother bumping up the difficulty.  And once you clear the ship of hostiles (at least on hard, not sure about ironman), it stays clear.  So, it's a true possibility that you will eventually destroy every enemy in the game.  You can play the game on a ""peaceful"" setting with no combat occuring unless you willingly harass the robotic guards, but this didn't seem very enticing to me as part of the fun was worrying about getting cut down by violent robo-security while rummaging through desk drawers.As everyone probably knows, there are multiple endings to be found in the game and I was able to uncover them all without resorting to a walkthrough.  You don't really even need to start the game over to get them all, but I took on a second playthrough anyway just to experience the action a second time.  While the Xanadu itself is a rather small setting, it's totally possible to get lost a few times and for a fairly short horror game (the norm mostly these days), there's a surprising amount to find, see and do in the time you spend with it.  I recommend a deliberate pace and taking your time, because it did feel rewarding gathering most of the achievements in this game (I'm at 84% right now).  Overall, Xanadu was alot of fun to play and I'm completely happy with the money spent on this one.  It's not perfect but it does more than enough to please horror fans that have seen/done most everything in the genre like myself.Pros:-Dark, intriguing storyline unfolds in a captivating minimalism-Great setting recalls classic horror/sci-fi film and games from the past-Excllent sound design with well-done voiceovers-Gameplay is devoid of hand-holding which allows you to experience the game at your own pace-Atmospheric graphics are not high end but get the job done-Fun Steam achievements worth spending time to gather-Multiple endings-Combat is fun and satisfyingCons:-Despite its general enjoyability and replay value, Xanadu is fairly short-Sometimes the graphics are a little too blocky-Controls are solid but not overly tight leading to a few uncessary deaths-You can get all of the endings without effectively starting the game over-Only a scant few weapon choices (a secret gun or two would have been fun to find)Final score:  8/10Verdict:  Xanadu would make a good double-header with other offbeat FPS horror adventures like Betrayer.  It's a different ball of wax than something like Betrayer with its own very unique flavor.  I've been pretty hooked on working and playing through Deadcore when I started Xanadu but as soon as I started this game I had to put Deadcore down for the time being.  Spirits of Xanadu sucked me in and I immediately had to dedicate my free gaming time over the last two days consistently to Spirits of Xanadu and only it once I got started and I totally enjoyed the experience!"
