,Recommended,312230,15070241,"Posted: 26 March, 2015",all,Shadix,"A very nice homage to the ideas behind SS2, a good buy for the price IMO, but 13 bucks might be a bit skeptical for those who aren't die hards of SS2 memorabilia."
,Recommended,312230,29307678,Posted: 16 January,all,Kryyss,"What would happen, if you took System Shock 2 and stripped away all of the RPG elements and turned it into a short story? Well, you'd get Spirits of Xanadu.Without a doubt this game will satisfy a bit of that itch you may have waiting for the system shock 1 remake that is currently in development. (http://systemshock.com/) But it is by no means going to satisfy you entirely. The atmosphere in SoX begins with the typical scenaro of having a shipwide blackout due to a power issue. It sets the tone nicely with some bizzare insanity effects and hallucinations but stumbles over itself in several places due to counter-productive design. For example, every time you 'die' you respawn in the Brig which is right next to the bridge so you sometimes find this as being helpful. This respawning mechanic actually sucks a ton of the tension out of the game and makes it less enjoyable in some ways but also mercifully less frustrating at others. I'm talking of course of the suicide-bots. In system SS2 style, all the robots in the game will respawn even in areas you have previously cleared and this helps the game to maintain the tension even when revisiting parts of the ship. But the design of these bots is really not very balanced. Can you outrun them? No, they run as fast as the player. Can you gun them down while back peddling? Almost. The only way to survive is to actually run to a gravity-elevator or find a raised platform but both of these means of escape are rarely available on board the Xanadu.In short, unless you encounter them at quite a distance then you're almost certain to die. This really needs to be adjusted because they become a real pain. But as I said, the respawning mechanic is a blessing when it comes to these kinds of deaths. Also, the creepy atmosphere is lost once you restore power to the ship and then it becomes far less tense. I'd actually go so far as to sugget the developers patch this to go from the shipwide black-out to dimmed emergency lighting which will maintain the atmosphere but allow you to see more clearly than the flashlight allows for alone.The storyline is delivered in typical SystemShock/DeusEx style with you discovering written logs, audio recordings and even post-it notes scattered around the place. Furthermore the developers have been devious enough to really require the player to think hard in order to achieve some of the more difficult puzzles. Speaking of the puzzles, they are nicely varied and not simply a 'find key, take key to this area - rinse and repeat' which often plagues many FPS puzzle games or walking simulators. To give you one example, you come across a whiteboard with some engineering notes and some numbers written in two columns upside down. This doesn't mean much at first until you notice a nearby room with certain systems offline and on the panels are buttons with numbers that, when pressed, sum together to produce a voltage. Put simply, the whiteboard tells you what voltage each subsystem needs and you need to do a little math to figure out which buttons produce the correct total. It's not rocket science, but its a nice brain teaser and produces that pleasing 'Ah ha!' moment when the solution to puzzles suddenly come together in your mind. SoX does this many times and does it very well.Visually the game won't win any awards but this is certainly one of the times when the gameplay itself is the greatest appeal. The voice acting on the audio logs themselves is fantastic and the storyline, while not very original, is presented in a way that is entertaining. My only complaint is that the strong language used in one of the audio logs was completely unessersary and when its being shouted at the top of the actors voice you really have to wonder why the developers felt that was required. Thankfully I was playing the game with my headphones on because my children were in the room and they hear enough of that kind of language at school.Spirits of Xanadu currently retails for a reasonable price of £7 and, although I picked it up on discount, I would honestly say it is worth the normal asking price if you don't mind how short the game is. There are two different endings which adds to the replay value but you are really going to have to work those brain-cells to achieve the 'failed mission' ending. I really hope we see more from this development team in the future because they have some really talented people on-board."
