76561198107315646,Not Recommended,312230,21610989,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,steven340,"I was quite looking forward to this game, as I love a good Sci-fi game setting. The concept sounded good, some good reviews also helped sway my decision to purchase the game, however I think my mistake was probably playing Alien Isolation before playing this game.Both these games have a very similar storyline, both set in space and on an abandoned space station where strange things have happened (we'll say no more to avoid spoiling it for anyone}, and of course we go in by ourselves to find out whats been going on. On paper the story is sound but in practise the Spirits of Xanadu left me feeling like I was back in the 1990s. The visual style can be forgiven somewhat, as I was fairly prepared for that after seeing the video on the store page. What I didn't expect to find is a virtually non-existant learning curve when it comes dealing with the kamikaze style robots onboard who immediately start shooting at you almost as soon as you set foot on the station. You have a weapon of course too which comes in pretty damn handy straight away, not like in Alien Isolation where you picked up weapons over time, but at least in that game you didn't have quite a much to deal with from the start, and you were very capable of sneaking past the enemy and avoiding any combat.In Spirits of Xanadu however it was almost a regular occurrance, and one that is immediately so frustrating that for me anyway I decided it was too much too soon, and gave up. It seemed like gaming had taken a gigantic step backwards in terms of playability.I can appreciate that combat in games like these is a necessary requirement, but when there is very little (or not at all in this case) learning curve to ease you into a particularly simple and dare I say it 'old style' of shooting game, reminiscent of playing Doom many years ago, just with plainer graphics and simpler but just as deadlier A.I.Yes I am over 40 and have played many games of this kind before, but frankly this game needs a lot more work to become a more enjoyable gaming experience."
