,Recommended,312230,21172115,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,Anterk,"What we have here is either a really, really short shooter on a spaceship or a very, very deep atmospheric adventure in space. You're pretty much free to play the game either way. As the sort fo person who hates Adventure games and crawling over every inch of a level just to find an item I really appreciate the open design.If you play this like a shooter you will probably get the bad ending and, if you can't get into the atmosphere, you won't have much fun. The game has the steady pace and mystery of Alien, and once you've killed all the robot enemies the ship will become very quiet.There are two things I didn't like: the length and overuse of the shellshock effect. The game felt so short it was like getting a teaspoon of a new flavor of icecream and then being told to go home because the shop is closing forever. It actually upset me a little bit. Sure, you can extend the length by hunting down all the pages and masks and nonsense but that's boring and annoying when your only companion is the shellshock effect.What do I mean by shellshock effect? I mean that flash followed by an approximation of the character's ears ringing. The screen flashes and your ears ring far, far too often for the effect to remain anything but aggravating. Plus I played shooters through the CoD era so I've experienced the shellshock effect so much it's become a painful cliche. I thought it would stop after a while but I never seemed to reach a point when I was safe from it. Part of the reason I'm accepting the bad ending and leaving the others for YouTube is simply so I don't have to put up with anymore shellshock.Good. Has problems, but still good."
